{
  "answer": "**Kātyāyana Smṛti** and **Viṣṇu Smṛti** are the primary works in the corpus that contain rules concerning the ordeal of fire (*agni*) as a judicial test, particularly in the context of determining guilt in cases like theft. These are ancient Indian Dharmaśāstra texts outlining when to apply it (e.g., based on the value stolen or caste), to whom it should not be administered (e.g., blacksmiths, lepers), and procedural details.[^1][^2][^3][^4][^5]\n\n**Traité de Législation: VOL II** by Charles Comte mentions the ordeal of fire descriptively as a judicial practice observed among certain African peoples (holding a burning coal), but it does not provide prescriptive rules.[^6]\n\nNo other works in the corpus cover this topic.\n\n[^1]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 32, [p-c8377d](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/32/translation/#p-c8377d/).\n\n[^2]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 33, [p-9f579b](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/33/translation/#p-9f579b/).\n\n[^3]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 33, [p-c24edd](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/33/translation/#p-c24edd/).\n\n[^4]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 35, [p-df4cd3](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/35/translation/#p-df4cd3/).\n\n[^5]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 9, [p-d2dfbe](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/09/translation/#p-d2dfbe/).\n\n[^6]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, Chapter 27, [p-908516](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/27/translation/#p-908516/).",
